@AshleyyySutton But I guess it's problematic for people who live paycheck-to-paycheck and expect a big windfall at the beginning of the new year.  You won't be getting it in one lump sum, so you have to be more mindful during the year.

Yay!  Fiscal responsibility!
full_text(utf-8): b"@AshleyyySutton But I guess it's problematic for people who live paycheck-to-paycheck and expect a big windfall at the beginning of the new year.  You won't be getting it in one lump sum, so you have to be more mindful during the year.\n\nYay!  Fiscal responsibility!"

full_text: @AshleyyySutton So it's not really good or bad, but people are going to be upset because they think that they should ALWAYS get a big refund, when a refund is basically a loan that you gave to the IRS for a year that they pay back in April.
full_text(utf-8): b"@AshleyyySutton So it's not really good or bad, but people are going to be upset because they think that they should ALWAYS get a big refund, when a refund is basically a loan that you gave to the IRS for a year that they pay back in April."

full_text: @AshleyyySutton If I'm getting the $10k with the smaller refund, I'm getting $42 with each paycheck I receive (which most people wouldn't even notice).   So it feels like I'm getting ripped off if I don't get that $1,000 refund, even though at the end of the year I'm getting the same amount.
full_text(utf-8): b"@AshleyyySutton If I'm getting the $10k with the smaller refund, I'm getting $42 with each paycheck I receive (which most people wouldn't even notice).   So it feels like I'm getting ripped off if I don't get that $1,000 refund, even though at the end of the year I'm getting the same amount."

full_text: @AshleyyySutton From a logical perspective, it doesn't matter.  If I get paid $9,000 and get a refund of $1,000 it's the same as me getting paid $10,000 during the year and getting no refund.  But people focus on the refund and not the individual paychecks that they receive.
full_text(utf-8): b"@AshleyyySutton From a logical perspective, it doesn't matter.  If I get paid $9,000 and get a refund of $1,000 it's the same as me getting paid $10,000 during the year and getting no refund.  But people focus on the refund and not the individual paychecks that they receive."
